The aqueous N-doped CNDs showed two typical absorption peaks at 219 and 355 nm (Fig. 5
                        a), contributed from π-π* transitions of the CC bonds and n-π* transitions of the CO bonds, respectively. In the fluorescence spectra, the CNDs had an emission maximum at 432 nm at the excitation of 370 nm, and displayed a bright blue color under 365 nm UV light, however, they displayed a light yellow color in the daylight (Fig. 5a). Herein, we also found that CNDs displayed a clear dependence of photoluminescence wavelength and intensity on excitation wavelength [4,25]. The fluorescence emission of CNDs increased in intensity as the excitation wavelength was changed from 330 to 370 nm, and reached a maximum when we used the 370 nm excitation wavelength. This was followed by a decrease, with an obvious red shift from 432 to 445 nm when we changed the excitation wavelength from 370 to 390 nm (Fig. 5b), which is a typical characteristic in fluorescent carbon materials [4]. We measured the fluorescence quantum yield of the synthesized N-doped CNDs by using quinine sulfate as a standard. The diammonium hydrogen citrate produced fluorescent CNDs with a high quantum yield of about 26.8%, which was obviously higher than that of the CNDs prepared from other carbon sources (Table 1
                        ), such as disodium hydrogen citrate, citric acid, ammonium oxalate, and ammonium acetate. Moreover, it was obvious that the fluorescence intensity of the CNDs prepared by diammonium hydrogen citrate as a carbon source were stronger than that of the CNDs prepared by other carbon sources (Fig. S8).
